<LP>
   PRUDENTIAL-BACHE will post a $250 million loss for 1990,
one of the worst performances ever by a U.S. brokerage firm.
Its parent, Prudential Insurance, is adding more than $200
million in new capital to bolster the sagging firm. The big
loss also raised new questions about how long George Ball
will remain as chairman of Prudential-Bache.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Merck disclosed that it developed a novel type of drug to
fight the AIDS virus and that it began pilot tests of the
drug in humans last month.
   ---
   Rostenkowski said he no longer plans to reintroduce early
in January a proposed surtax on millionaires. President Bush,
meantime, said he won't include his twice-failed proposal to
cut capital-gains taxes as part of his fiscal 1992 budget
request.
   ---
   The Big Board's new chairman, William Donaldson, wants to
greatly expand the number of foreign stocks traded on the
exchange. Mr. Donaldson will take office Jan. 1.
   ---
   The dollar surged against other major currencies amid a
growing threat of political instability in the Soviet Union.
U.S. markets mostly shrugged off the developments.
   ---
   Sunbelt Savings' ex-owner, Edwin T. McBirney III, is
expected to plead guilty today to federal criminal charges,
less than 24 hours after a jury convicted Don R. Dixon,
ex-owner of Vernon S&amp;L in Dallas.
   ---
   Bank of New England bondholders tentatively agreed to a
debt-for-equity swap that would give them 92% of the ailing
bank's common stock.
                                                                                                       

   Bank of Boston said it will have a "substantial loss" in
the fourth quarter, ensuring a loss for the full year.
   ---
   BankAmerica plans to bid to acquire failed thrifts in
Texas, New Mexico and California as part of its effort to
dominate retail banking in the West, company executives said.
   ---
   California's Supreme Court issued two rulings that could
limit employees' ability to seek damages for emotional
distress stemming from wrongful discharge. But another ruling
aids employees in some cases.
   ---
   Consumer spending inched up 0.1% in November as incomes
increased only slightly, suggesting consumers won't
contribute to economic strength in the next few months.
   ---
   Short interest showed little change on both the Big Board
and Amex in the month ended Dec. 14, after rising strongly
for the past year.
   ---
   GE was selected to design the engine for Japan's
controversial FSX fighter plane over United Technologies'
Pratt &amp; Whitney division.
   ---
   Midwest manufacturers are feeling the pinch of the weak
economy, largely due to auto industry cutbacks.
   ---
   Capital spending plans are being scaled back. In a
government survey, businesses said they plan to raise
spending a cautious 2.4% in 1991.
